# üîµ What is a Fragment?

In React:

üëâ A component must return **only ONE root element**

‚ùå This is WRONG:

```jsx
return (
  <h1>Hello</h1>
  <p>Welcome</p>
);
```

React will give error because there are two root elements.

---

# üßÝ Why This Restriction?

Because React expects:

> Component = Single JSX tree

So we usually wrap elements inside a `<div>`.

---

# üîµ 1Ô∏è‚É£ Normal Way (Using div)

```jsx
import React from "react";

export default function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Hello Venky</h1>
      <p>Welcome to React</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

‚úî Works
‚ùå But adds extra `<div>` in DOM

Sometimes that extra div is unnecessary.

---

# üîµ 2Ô∏è‚É£ Using Fragment (Better Way)

Instead of `<div>`, we use **Fragment**.

---

## ‚úÖ Method 1: React.Fragment

```jsx
import React from "react";

export default function App() {
  return (
    <React.Fragment>
      <h1>Hello Venky</h1>
      <p>Welcome to React</p>
    </React.Fragment>
  );
}
```

‚úî No extra div added in DOM
‚úî Cleaner HTML

---

## ‚úÖ Method 2: Short Syntax (Most Common)

```jsx
import React from "react";

export default function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <h1>Hello Venky</h1>
      <p>Welcome to React</p>
    </>
  );
}
```

üëâ `<> </>` is shortcut for Fragment
üëâ Most used in real projects

---

# üîé What Happens in DOM?

If you use `<div>`:

```html
<div>
  <h1>Hello</h1>
  <p>Welcome</p>
</div>
```

If you use Fragment:

```html
<h1>Hello</h1>
<p>Welcome</p>
```

No extra wrapper.

---

# üîµ When Fragments Are Very Useful

## üéØ Example: Returning List Items

‚ùå Wrong:

```jsx
function List() {
  return (
    <div>
      <li>Java</li>
      <li>React</li>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This creates invalid HTML:

```html
<ul>
  <div>
    <li>Java</li>
    <li>React</li>
  </div>
</ul>
```

---

‚úÖ Correct using Fragment:

```jsx
function List() {
  return (
    <>
      <li>Java</li>
      <li>React</li>
    </>
  );
}
```

Now it becomes valid:

```html
<ul>
  <li>Java</li>
  <li>React</li>
</ul>
```

