# üîµ Why Do We Split Components?

In React, we don‚Äôt put everything inside one big component.

Instead:

üëâ We break UI into **small pieces**
üëâ Each piece has **one responsibility**

This makes code:

* Easy to read
* Easy to reuse
* Easy to debug

---

# üü¢ 1Ô∏è‚É£ Splitting Component by **Feature**

### ‚úÖ What is "Feature"?

Feature = A logical part of the application.

For example in a Todo App:

* Add Todo
* List Todos
* Delete Todo
* Header

Each of these is a **feature**.

---

## üßÝ Simple Rule:

üëâ If something does a separate job ‚Üí make it a separate component.

---

### ‚ùå Bad Example (Everything in one component)

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Todo App</h1>
      <input />
      <button>Add</button>
      <ul>
        <li>Task 1</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Everything is mixed.

---

### ‚úÖ Good Example (Split by Feature)

```jsx
function Header() {
  return <h1>Todo App</h1>;
}

function AddTodo() {
  return (
    <>
      <input />
      <button>Add</button>
    </>
  );
}

function TodoList() {
  return (
    <ul>
      <li>Task 1</li>
    </ul>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <AddTodo />
      <TodoList />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Now:

* `Header` ‚Üí shows title
* `AddTodo` ‚Üí handles adding
* `TodoList` ‚Üí shows list

This is **splitting by feature**.

---

# üü¢ 2Ô∏è‚É£ Splitting Component by **State**

Now this is very important üî•

### üßÝ First Understand State

State = Data that changes.

Example:

* Counter value
* Input text
* Logged-in user
* Todo list

---

## üö® Important Rule

üëâ The component that **owns the state** should control it.
üëâ Other components receive data using props.

---

## Example: Counter App

### ‚ùå Bad Example (Everything in one component)

```jsx
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{count}</h2>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>+</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Small example is fine.

But in real app, this becomes messy.

---

## ‚úÖ Split by State Responsibility

```jsx
function Display({ count }) {
  return <h2>{count}</h2>;
}

function Button({ onIncrement }) {
  return <button onClick={onIncrement}>+</button>;
}

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);

  function handleIncrement() {
    setCount(count + 1);
  }

  return (
    <div>
      <Display count={count} />
      <Button onIncrement={handleIncrement} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

### üî• What Happened Here?

* `Counter` ‚Üí owns state
* `Display` ‚Üí only shows data
* `Button` ‚Üí only triggers action

This is **splitting by state responsibility**.

---

# üü£ When Should You Split by Feature?

‚úî When UI has different logical sections
‚úî When something can be reused
‚úî When component becomes too big

---

# üü£ When Should You Split by State?

‚úî When multiple parts need same state
‚úî When UI and logic should be separated
‚úî When you want better maintainability

---

# üßÝ Simple Real-World Analogy

Imagine a restaurant:

* Chef ‚Üí Handles cooking (state owner)
* Waiter ‚Üí Displays food (display component)
* Cashier ‚Üí Handles payment (action component)

Each has separate responsibility.

That‚Äôs how React components should be.

---

# üéØ Final Simple Difference

| Split by Feature      | Split by State                   |
| --------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Based on UI parts     | Based on data responsibility     |
| Header, Sidebar, Form | State owner + display components |
| Improves structure    | Improves data flow               |

