# üî¥ Problem: Props Are Not Forwarded to Inner Elements

This usually happens when:

üëâ You pass props to a component
üëâ But that component does NOT pass them to the actual HTML element inside

So the props ‚Äústop‚Äù there.

---

# üßÝ Simple Example

### Step 1: Parent sends props

```jsx
function App() {
  return <Button type="submit" />;
}
```

You are sending:

```
type="submit"
```

---

### Step 2: Button component

```jsx
function Button() {
  return <button>Click Me</button>;
}
```

‚öÝ Problem:

You sent `type="submit"`
But Button did NOT receive or pass it.

So the real `<button>` does NOT get `type="submit"`.

That means:

üëâ Props are NOT forwarded
üëâ They are lost

---

# üü¢ Correct Way (Forward Props)

We must receive props and pass them inside.

```jsx
function Button(props) {
  return <button type={props.type}>Click Me</button>;
}
```

Now it works.

---

# üü£ Even Better Way (Forward Everything Automatically)

React gives a simple pattern using **spread operator**

```jsx
function Button(props) {
  return <button {...props}>Click Me</button>;
}
```

What this does:

If parent sends:

```jsx
<Button type="submit" disabled />
```

Then inside:

```jsx
<button type="submit" disabled>
```

All props are forwarded automatically.

---

# üî• Why This Problem Happens

Because custom components are NOT real HTML elements.

When you write:

```jsx
<Button type="submit" />
```

React does NOT automatically attach `type` to inner `<button>`.

You must forward it manually.

---

# üßÝ Very Simple Real-Life Analogy

Imagine:

You give a parcel üì¶ to a delivery manager.

If manager keeps it and doesn‚Äôt pass to worker ‚Üí parcel never reaches customer.

Same here:

Parent ‚Üí Component ‚Üí HTML element

If component does not forward ‚Üí props stop there.

---

# üéØ One-Line Understanding

> Props are not forwarded because custom components do NOT automatically pass props to inner HTML elements.

You must forward them using:

```jsx
{...props}
```

